{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489138","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489138"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:06:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:06:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"601"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/601"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.07,0.12,0.61,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"601"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95139"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/601"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"601"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78106"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"130"},{"type":"tags","id":"3307"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9798"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1975"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1980"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42109"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95139"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner for follow-up of his hypertension and type 2 diabetes. He is currently on perindopril, amlodipine, hydrochlorothiazide and metformin, and his blood pressure and diabetes have been well controlled over the past three years, with no changes to his medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is now complaining of episodes of intermittent headaches and palpitations, accompanied by feelings of extreme anxiety. These episodes occur distinctly, approximately three times a week and have been present for about three months. He has also noticed his blood glucose levels have been higher than usual recently, with no recent changes to his diet. His blood pressure today is 160/100 mmHg and a random BGL is 15mmol/L. His weight has not changed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["24hr urinary cortisol","Plasma aldosterone/renin ratio","Thyroid function tests","24hr urinary fractionated metanephrines and catecholamines","MRI head"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAlthough rare, phaeochromocytoma is the top differential in this man due to his uncontrolled hypertension, recurrent episodic headaches, palpitations, and anxiety, and increased blood glucose levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis tumour in the adrenal gland results in excessive production of adrenaline, and classically presents with a triad of intermittent headaches, palpitations and diaphoresis (although patients do not always present with all three symptoms). It can also cause sustained or paroxysmal hypertension. Furthermore, his BGLs are most likely elevated due to the adrenaline acting as a counter-regulatory hormone. The weight may remain stable or decrease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E24hr urinary fractionated metanephrines and catecholamines\u003C/strong\u003E is an important screening test for phaeochromocytoma. It is important to recognise that it may be normal in some cases if the patient\u0027s symptoms are intermittent, as the tumour may discharge episodically. It is important then to take the collection just after patient has had symptoms. Testing for plasma metanephrines has a higher sensitivity compared with 24-hour urinary collection, but a lower specificity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA 24hr urinary cortisol is the screening test for Cushing\u0027s syndrome. While Cushing\u0027s may explain the worsening BGLs and hypertension, it is unlikely to be causing palpitations and headaches in such an episodic manner, and his weight would have most likely increased.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlasma aldosterone/renin ratio is the screening test for primary aldosteronism. This is the most common endocrinological cause of hypertension and must be considered when hypertension is refractory to treatment. However, it would not be causing the intermittent headaches, palpitations or worsening BGLs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHyperthyroidism may be the cause of hypertension refractory to triple anti-hypertensive therapy. It may also explain his palpitations. However, it would not explain the headaches or worsening BGLs. His weight would also have likely dropped with hyperthyroidism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn MRI head would be useful if an ACTH-producing pituitary adenoma (Cushing\u0027s disease) was thought to be the cause of his symptoms, but it is less likely in this man given the palpitations and stable weight.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["24hr urinary fractionated metanephrines and catecholamines is an important screening test for pheochromocytoma and should be done promptly after development of symptoms."],"references":["Miller RA, Ohrt DW. Pheochromocytoma - review and biochemical workup. S D Med. 2013 Jul;66(7):267, 269-70. PMID: 23957112.","Davison AS, Jones DM, Ruthven S, Helliwell T, Shore SL. Clinical evaluation and treatment of phaeochromocytoma. Ann Clin Biochem. 2018 Jan;55(1):34-48. doi: 10.1177/0004563217739931. Epub 2017 Nov 8. PMID: 29027806."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78106"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"601"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78106","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78106"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-27T11:10:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-27T11:15:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"601"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95139"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/130"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Pheochromocytoma","s